page.text: The Willy Street Co-op is a member-owned grocery store located at 1221 Williamson St. in Madison, WI.
The approximately 20,000 sq. ft., one-story building is situated on a 1.3 acre lot bounded by Williamson
St. in the front and Jenifer St. in the back. The property shares a block between Few St. and Baldwin St.
with a Madison fire station, smaller retail establishments, and numerous residences.
The parking lot for the Co-op contains approximately 50 parking stalls, which are split between a larger
area on the northeast side of the building, and a smaller section that primarily lies along the west side of
the store. The only driveway into and out of the lot is accessed from Williamson St. between the two
parking areas. The geometry of the driveway and lot is not well-suited for vehicular entry / exit, as
entering vehicles must immediately turn left or right instead of accessing an aisle, and circulation of
vehicles attempting to find a parking spot brings most of those cars back across the driveway and the
entrance to the store. The short driveway throat length creates problems when more than one vehicle is
waiting to exit the lot, especially if there are any parked cars loading or unloading customers and
groceries in the vicinity of the driveway. The Co-op and surrounding areas are also utilized by a
substantial number of pedestrians and bicyclists, which raises additional safety concerns.
Williamson St. is identified by the City of Madison as a standard arterial, which means that the roadway
is primarily used for traffic mobility rather than land access, although many driveways serving
commercial and residential uses are found on Williamson St. The roadway contains four total lanes, two
in each direction. However, the outside lane in each direction is available for parking at all times except
the peak traffic hours, so for most of the day, the street only has one through traffic lane in each direction.
The average weekday traffic volume (AWT) on Williamson St. near the Co-op in 2007 was 26,400
vehicles, according to the City. There are traffic signals at the intersections of Williamson St. with
Baldwin St. (approximately 300 feet east of the Co-op driveway) and Ingersoll St. (one-and-a-half blocks
west of the Co-op). Observation of traffic indicates that queuing of eastbound vehicles due to the traffic
signal at Baldwin St. will often extend past the Co-op driveway, even during the evening rush hour when
the parking lane is available as an additional traffic lane for eastbound traffic. This creates significant
problems at the Co-op driveway, as vehicles are often unable to enter or leave the parking lot unless
drivers on Williamson St. leave space and wave drivers into or out of the lot.
Baldwin St. is identified as a collector by the City, which means it has roughly an equal purpose for
traffic mobility and land access. The 2007 ADT on Baldwin St is approximately 4,900 north of
Williamson St, but only 2,800 south of Williamson, reflecting the use of Baldwin as a connection
between Williamson St and East Washington Ave, a primary arterial. Jenifer St. and Few St. are
considered local streets, which primarily serve to access adjacent land uses, and carry ADT volumes of
less than 3,000 per day. Jenifer St and Baldwin St. also service a number of Madison Metro transit
As previously noted, the Co-op’s only vehicle entrance / exit point is on Williamson St., approximately
300 feet west of a signalized intersection at Baldwin St. A combination of heavy traffic volumes and
vehicle queuing due to the traffic signal combine to create relatively few opportunities for Co-op
customers to enter and exit the parking lot. Left turns into or out of the lot are especially difficult.
Vehicles are legally prohibited from making a left-turn when exiting the parking lot between 7:30 - 9:30
AM and 4:30 – 7:00 PM, although some vehicles were observed ignoring this restriction. At times of
heaviest traffic, there are very few gaps in traffic that allow vehicles to enter or exit the lot. The majority
of gaps are often created by eastbound vehicles on Williamson St. stopping in positions that allow
sufficient room for westbound vehicles to turn left and enter the parking lot and/or exiting vehicles to turn
onto Williamson St. This can also lead to additional safety concerns, as the courtesy of a driver who
stops and leaves an opening may create a false sense of security for the driver of the turning vehicle, who
may not be able to see (or be seen by) drivers of moving vehicles in other lanes. When the left-turn
prohibition is in effect, or at other times when traffic is heavy, drivers exiting the Co-op who may
ultimately wish to travel west towards downtown Madison may be forced to turn right (east) onto
Williamson St, and then subsequently turn at Baldwin St and one of a number of other streets (including
Jenifer St, Wilson St, and East Washington Ave.) in order to return westbound. Figures 1 through 4 below
illustrate examples of vehicle queuing that affect operations at the Co-op driveway:

page.text: The Co-op property currently includes a bicycle / pedestrian access point to / from Jenifer St at the end of
the parking area along the west side of the building. This location used to be an additional vehicular
access point to the property under previous ownership and use of the property. Due to the traffic and
safety problems associated with the lone access point at Williamson St., the Co-op decided to explore the
possibility of reopening the Jenifer St. access point to vehicular traffic. The proposal would limit access
to a right-turn-only, exit-only movement onto Jenifer St. A driveway in this location could be designed
with a narrow width and channelization in order to make it difficult for vehicles to turn left onto Jenifer St
and for any vehicles to enter the Co-op from Jenifer St. The location of the proposed exit is shown in
The following sections of this report include summaries of the data collection and traffic analysis
performed in order to estimate the number of vehicles that may use a second exit, and the impacts on both
the current driveway and other areas of or adjacent to the Co-op property.
The first portion of the traffic study included the collection of various traffic data, including data
previously obtained by the City of Madison, new volume and turning-movement counts at the Co-op
driveway and adjacent streets and intersections, and crash data on the block of Williamson St. fronting the
Co-op. Summary data from the new traffic counts are included in the appendix.
Turning movement counts were performed at the intersection of Williamson St with the Co-op driveway
on two different weekdays in November: a normal Tuesday, and the first Wednesday of the month (the
Co-op’s “Wellness Wednesday”, which often results in increased customer traffic). In both cases, the
overall peak hour for traffic occurred at 4:30 – 5:30 PM, consistent with a typical evening rush hour. The
peak traffic volumes were actually slightly lower on Wellness Wednesday, but only by approximately
3%. During the peak hour on Tuesday, there were 1196 eastbound vehicles and 581 westbound vehicles
approaching the driveway on Williamson St. (about a 67% / 33% split), with 134 vehicles departing the
Co-op driveway from the south (14 of them turning left, despite the sign prohibiting left turns at that
Turning movement counts (from 3:00 to 6:00 PM only) were also conducted at the intersections of
Williamson St. with Ingersoll St. and Baldwin St. on typical weekdays. These counts confirmed the
typical peak hour of 4:30 – 5:30 PM. The volumes on Williamson St were also within approximately 3%
of the volumes from the counts at the Co-op driveway, which increases the confidence level that these
counts represent typical traffic conditions in the evening rush hour.
A tube count was conducted on Jenifer St behind the Co-op from a Tuesday afternoon through mid-day
Friday. The count indicated an average daily traffic volume of approximately 1800 vehicles, with the
heaviest volumes occurring from 4:00 – 7:00 PM. The actual peak hour of 5:30 – 6:30 PM on Jenifer St
was different than the 4:30 – 5:30 PM peak hour on Williamson St. During the 4:30 – 5:30 hour, traffic
on Jenifer St averaged 166 vehicles, while the peak hour on Jenifer St. of 5:30 – 6:30 PM averaged 180

page.text: A gap study was also conducted on Williamson St. at the Co-op driveway. A gap study is used to
determine the amount of various size gaps in traffic that can be used by vehicles turning or crossing from
a minor street (in this case, the driveway) onto a major street (Williamson St). The Highway Capacity
Manual indicates that gaps of 6 to 7 seconds are required for a vehicle to turn right onto the major street,
and 7 to 7.5 seconds to turn left. The gap study conducted at the driveway indicated that in the peak hour,
there were approximately 55 gaps in eastbound traffic sufficient for a vehicle to turn right onto
Williamson Street, and approximately 20 gaps in traffic in both directions sufficient for vehicles to turn
left. It should be noted that many of these gaps were long enough for more than one vehicle to turn, but
also that some of these gaps occurred when there were no vehicles waiting to turn.
A two-hour survey of customers was conducted in front of the Co-op during an evening peak period.
Customers were asked if they drove to the Co-op, and if so, what direction would they be heading when
they left on this trip (or their “usual” trip) to the Co-op. Of the 46 respondents, 63% indicated they would
head east, and 37% would head west. This result is close to the 67% eastbound / 33% westbound split in
traffic found on Williamson St. during the evening rush hour. Additional comments from surveyed
customers are included in the Appendix.
Finally, crash data for the years 2002 – 2007 was obtained from the City of Madison for the block of
Williamson St. between Few St. and Baldwin St. This data represents crashes that were reported to the
Madison Police Department. Crashes were separated between those that occurred at intersections versus
those in the mid-block. From 2002 – 2007, the number of mid-block crashes on Williamson St. ranged
from six to ten per year, with an average of 7.8 per year, while the number of intersection crashes (at Few
St. and Ingersoll St. combined) ranged from one to three per year, with an average of 2.2 per year.
Accident reports from the Madison PD were available for some of the crashes from 2005 to 2007, but the
summary data from the City included basic stick diagrams of the accidents on a map for all years. A large
number of the crashes were rear-end collisions, primarily in the eastbound direction, most likely due to
sudden stops resulting from traffic signal operations or heavy congestion. However, out of the 47 total
mid-block crashes, nine crashes were either identified in the accident reports or shown on the maps to
directly involve vehicles turning into or out of the Co-op parking lot. Six of those involved vehicles
turning out of the Co-op, with the other three involving vehicles turning into the parking lot from
Williamson St. There may have been other rear-end crashes that were directly or indirectly related to the
traffic operations at the driveway, but whose cause was not clearly derived from the accident reports or
crash maps. Copies of the crash maps are included in the Appendix.
The traffic conditions were modeled in the traffic engineering software package Synchro / SimTraffic.
The segment of Williamson St. from Ingersoll St. to Baldwin St. was modeled, including the traffic
signals at Ingersoll and Baldwin. Traffic signal timing data was obtained from the City, and confirmed in
the field. The traffic signals affect operations at the Co-op driveway in a couple of key ways. First,
eastbound vehicles stopping at the signal at Baldwin often queue up to or past the Co-op driveway,
inhibiting vehicle movements into and out of the driveway. Second, the operations of the traffic signals
create platoons of vehicles on Williamson St., which can have both positive and negative impacts on the
operations the driveway. The platoons lead to longer stretches of time when there is continuous traffic in
front of the driveway, but also create gaps that would not otherwise occur with random arrivals.
During the evening rush hour, parking on the eastbound side of Williamson St. is prohibited, which
effectively creates a second vehicle traffic lane. With this second lane open, Williamson St. is able to
handle a much larger traffic volume, vehicle queues are shorter, and more frequent and larger gaps in
eastbound traffic are available. Under ideal conditions, with the second lane open, the intersection of
Williamson St and the Co-op is expected to operate fairly well. The average delay for vehicles departing
the Co-op is estimated at 33 seconds (Level of Service ‘D’), with 95% queue lengths of 74 feet
(approximately three vehicles). However, the operations of the nearby signalized intersection at Baldwin
St. can affect the operations of the driveway. The intersection at Baldwin functions fairly well (overall
Level of Service ‘C’), but the queue of eastbound vehicles frequently passes the Co-op driveway, which is
about 300 feet away. According to Synchro, in the PM peak hour, the 50% queue (representative of the
typical cycle for a traffic signal) is 355 feet, while the 95% queue length is estimated at 418 feet. This
general condition has been confirmed in the field during traffic counts and other observation times. As
previously mentioned, during these periods when the backup of traffic goes past the driveway, some
drivers will stop short of the driveway, allowing other vehicles to turn into and out of the driveway.
However, this can also create additional safety concerns as other drivers may fail to recognize the
To demonstrate the criticality of having the second eastbound lane available to traffic in the evening peak
period, the model was adjusted so that only one lane was available to traffic. This would represent times
when vehicles are still parked (and have yet to be towed) during the prohibited times, or when the second
lane is otherwise blocked, such as by the accumulation of plowed snow and ice. Under the same
volumes, this situation would result in a failing Level of Service ‘F’ at the intersection of Williamson St.
and Baldwin St., as well as for vehicles departing the Co-op at the driveway, which could experience
delays of over seven minutes and queues of 300 feet (approximately 12 – 15 vehicles). The queues of
eastbound vehicles stopped for the traffic signal at Baldwin St could exceed 900 feet, which would extend
well past Few St. towards Ingersoll St.
If the Co-op decides to pursue a second exit on Jenifer St, the impacts to the overall system should be
somewhat minimal. Based on the results of the traffic counts that showed 134 vehicles leaving the Co-op
in the evening peak hour, and the roughly 65% eastbound / 35% westbound split of traffic shown both by
the traffic counts and the driver survey, an estimated 45 vehicles would use the rear exit in that hour. This
assumes that all vehicles leaving the Co-op that intend to travel westbound would use this exit in place of
the front exit on Williamson St. This could either by choice as vehicles find it difficult to turn left onto
Williamson St., or by enhanced recognition or enforcement of the left-turn prohibition. Since the traffic
counts found that only 14 vehicles turned left out of the existing driveway in the peak hour, an estimated
31 vehicles that would otherwise prefer to turn left and head west are, in fact, turning right out of the
driveway, and presumably using Baldwin St., Jenifer St., and / or other streets to return to the west. Thus,
traffic on those streets east of the Co-op may actually be reduced slightly by the use of a second exit onto
As shown in the traffic counts, the current volume on Jenifer St from 4:30 to 5:30 PM is approximately
166 vehicles, so an addition of up to 45 additional vehicles would have a relatively minor impact on
traffic conditions. However, due to the fairly heavy presence of pedestrians and bicyclists, the design of
such an exit should be carefully designed to maximize safety and maintain pedestrian / bicyclist access, as
well as preventing left turns out of the driveway or any vehicles from entering the Co-op. Re-opening the
driveway may result in the loss of at least one parking stall on Jenifer St.
Removing 45 vehicles from the front driveway would improve the performance of that driveway. Based
on Synchro modeling, the average delay for vehicles leaving the driveway would decrease from 33
seconds to 16 seconds. The impacts on the signalized intersections at Baldwin St. and Ingersoll St. would
be somewhat minimal. The reduced traffic at Baldwin would result in slight improvements in delays
(24.4 to 22.6 seconds per vehicle) and queue lengths (reduction of about 20 feet, or one vehicle length).
Assuming that all of the vehicles using the new exit would continue on Jenifer St to Ingersoll St., turn
right, then turn left at the traffic signal onto westbound Williamson St., the increased number of left turns
from Ingersoll St. to westbound Williamson St. would only result in slight increases in overall delays at
the intersection, from 12.7 to 13.9 seconds per vehicle.
While it is difficult to quantify any possible reductions in crashes due to the possible additional exit, it is
reasonable to assume that reducing the number of vehicles attempting to turn out of the existing driveway,
especially left turns, onto a congested street such as Williamson St. should lead to a reduction in crashes.
As previously mentioned, there were 47 reported mid-block crashes on the 1200 block of Williamson St.
between 2002 and 2007, of which at least nine were identified in accident reports or inferred from the
City’s crash maps as directly involving vehicles attempting to enter or leave the Co-op parking lot.
Other than re-opening the second driveway, there are other strategies that may improve the safety and
operations in the area of Williamson St and the existing Co-op driveway. Any alternative should be
carefully evaluated for potential benefits, as well as negative impacts, before implementation. These
strategies may include, but are not limited to, the following:
• Provide additional and / or improved signing to increase driver awareness of pedestrians,
• Extend times of and increase enforcement of ‘no-left-turn’ prohibition from Co-op driveway
• Implementation of ‘no-left-turn’ from westbound Williamson St. into Co-op driveway
• Extend times when no parking is allowed on Williamson St
• Remove parking spot(s) on westbound Williamson St. directly opposite Co-op driveway, to allow
through vehicles to bypass left-turning vehicles
• Remove parking spots on eastbound Williamson St immediately east and / or west of driveway to
• Alter signal timing at Williamson St. and Baldwin St. to reduce queuing (add left-turn signal for
• Improve coordination between traffic signals on Williamson St. at Ingersoll St. and Baldwin St.
to provide smooth traffic flow and additional gaps in traffic
• Increase enforcement of “no parking” and prohibit loading / unloading on portion of driveway
near the store entrance in order to improve vehicle movement
The lone existing access point to the Williamson St. Co-op is on a congested portion of Williamson St,
approximately 300 feet west of a traffic signal at Baldwin St. In the evening rush hour, vehicle queues
resulting from this signal often extend past the Co-op driveway, making access to and from the Co-op
difficult during the peak shopping time for the store. The area in front of the store and along Williamson
St. is also used by a large number of pedestrians and bicyclists, creating additional safety concerns. In
order to improve the safety and operations at the Co-op’s existing driveway and the adjacent portion of
Williamson St., the Co-op is considering making a request to re-open a second driveway onto Jenifer St,
which would only allow right-turn exits, and no incoming traffic. Based on traffic counts and a survey of
customers exiting the Co-op, a second exit may result in up to 45 vehicles using the rear exit instead of
the main driveway in the PM peak hour. This is not expected to significantly impact the traffic operations
of Jenifer St, which generally has peak hour volumes from 160 – 200 vehicles per hour in the evening.
The overall impact on intersections along Williamson St. should be relatively minor, with small
improvements to operations at the intersections of Williamson St. with the Co-op driveway and Baldwin
St., and a small increase in delay at Ingersoll St. If the rear exit was re-opened, careful consideration
should be given to the design to insure that only right-turn exits are allowed, and that safe conditions for
vehicles, pedestrians, and bicyclists are maintained. Other strategies, including additional restrictions on
parking and turning, may also be considered.
